  "review": "It's a fun film, but not a great one.br br I watched it the first time in the theater and didn't buy the dvd immediately.br br About 3 weeks later, I decided to buy it. It was the weekend of the annual Hollywood Film Festival. It was played during the official opening ceremony.br br I bought the dvd to watch it at home, but then I realized that it was the first feature film from director Adam Rifkin, and I wanted to see more of his movies.br br A lot of critics call this a comedy, and I suppose it is, but the subject matter and timing of events often leaves this more on the drama side.br br A young adult male protagonist named Ben has a tough decision to make. Either remain at his college or return home to his mother. His girlfriend Sarah is pregnant and he is torn between becoming a father and finishing his degree. He tells his story to his roommate and fellow college student Toby, who advises him to choose himself.br br A few months later, Ben returns to his hometown and confronts his mother. She's been dating a younger man who happens to be the father of her unborn child.br br Ben realizes that if he chooses to become a father, his mother must be forced to admit the truth of the pregnancy and accept the responsibility of raising a new child.br br The film shows a lot of interesting twists and turns. The characters' actions provoke a series of unexpected events.br br The premise is intriguing, and although not original, it is presented well. There are several plot arcs running concurrently, including an attempt by a young woman to prevent her father from killing himself.br br The movie touches on various themes such as relationships, morality, family, and suicide. It's not a perfect movie, but the subject matter makes it worthwhile. Some scenes may offend audiences, so viewers should be warned."  
